Based on the information you've provided, assuming all contracts are for 100 shares and no other investments are owned, an increase in stock price is more optimal for the position.

This is because the value of the sold call will be less than the value of the purchased call, resulting in a net short position. If the stock price increases, the difference between the sale and purchase will increase, and the net short position will lose value.

On the other hand, if the stock price decreases, the difference between the sale and purchase will decrease, potentially leading to gains from the net short position.

Therefore, in order to maximize returns, an increase in stock price is more optimal for the position.
